pringwood Books.\nISBN\n978-0-86254-111-8\n.\nArchived\nfrom the original on 24 September 2023\n. Retrieved\n18 November\n2020\n.\nFurther reading\nPais, Abraham\n(1983).\nSubtle Is the Lord: The Science and the Life of Albert Einstein\n(Third ed.). Oxford University Press.\nISBN\n978-0-19-520438-4\n.\nOCLC\n8195995\n.\nExternal links\nWikimedia Commons has media related to\nNobel Prize\n.\nListen to this article\n(\n30\nminutes\n)\nThis audio file\nwas created from a revision of this article dated 2 November 2016\n(\n2016-11-02\n)\n, and does not reflect subsequent edits.\n(\nAudio help\n·\nMore spoken articles\n)\nOfficial website\nNobel Prizes by universities and institutes\nv\nt\ne\nNobel Prizes\nLists of Nobel laureates\nNobel Prize medal\nPrizes\nChemistry\nEconomics\n1\nLiterature\nPeace\nPhysics\nPhysiology or Medicine\nLaureates\nby occupation\nHeads of state and government\nby year\nby subject\nChemistry\nEconomics\n1\nLiterature\nPeace\nPhysics\nPhysiology or Medicine\nby\npopulation\ngroup\nBengali\nBlack\nChristian\nFemale\nJewish\nLatin American\nNon-religious\nby continent\nand\nnationality\nAfrican\nEgyptian\nSouth African\nAsian\nArmenian\nChinese\nFilipino\nIndian\nIsraeli\nJapanese\nKorean\nPakistani\nTurkish\nVietnamese\nEuropean\nBelgian\nDanish\nGerman\nGreek\nHungarian\nIrish\nItalian\nPolish\nRomanian\nRussian\nSpanish\nSwedish\nSwiss\nWelsh\nOceanian\nAustralian\nNorth American\nAmerican\nMexican\nSouth American\nArgentine\nBrazilian\nVenezuelan\nby university\nCity University of New York\nColumbia University\nETH Zurich\nHarvard University\nPrinceton University\nWashington University in St. Louis\nNominees\nCatholic priests and religious\nHeads of state and government\nCouples\nWomen\nby subject\nChemistry\n1901–1999\nEconomics\n1\n1901–1999\nLiterature\n1901–1999\n2000–present\nPeace\nIndividuals\n1900–1999\n2000–present\nOrganizations\nPhysics\n1901–1999\nPhysiology or Medicine\n1901–1999\nby groups\nPeace\nAFSC Nobel nominees\nPRIO Director's Shortlist\nby\nClarivate\nFemale\nChemistry\nEconomics\n1\nPhysics\nPhysiology or Medicine\nOrganisations\nNobel Foundation\nNobel Committees\nChemistry\nEconomics\n1\nLiterature\nPhysics\nPhysiology or Medicine\nNorwegian Nobel Committee\nNobel Assembly at the Karolinska Institute\nRelated\nControversies\nLiterature\nPhysics\nPeace\nAlfred Nobel\nBjörkborn Manor\nNobel Banquet\nNobel Laboratory\nLindau Nobel Laureate Meetings\nNobel Monument\nWorld Summit of Nobel Peace Laureates\nPrizes known as the \"Nobel\" of their fields\n1\nNobel Memorial Prize (not one of the original Nobel Prizes).\nv\nt\ne\n2025\nNobel Prize\nlaureates\nChemistry\nSusumu Kitagawa\n(Japan)\nRichard Robson\n(Australia, United Kingdom)\nOmar M. Yaghi\n(Palestine, Jordan, United States)\nLiterature\n(\n2025\n)\nLászló Krasznahorkai\n(Hungary)\nPeace\n(\n2025\n)\nMaría Corina Machado\n(Venezuela)\nPhysics\nJohn Clarke\n(United Kingdom)\nMichel H. Devoret\n(France)\nJohn M. Martinis\n(United States)\nPhysiology or Medicine\nMary E. Brunkow\n(United States)\nFred Ramsdell\n(United States)\nShimon Sakaguchi\n(Japan)\nEconomic Sciences\nJoel Mokyr\n(Netherlands, Israel, United States)\nPhilippe Aghion\n(France)\nPeter Howitt\n(Canada)\nNobel Prize recipients\n2020\n2021\n2022\n2023\n2024\n2025\n2026\nAuthority control databases\nInternational\nGND\nNational\nUnited States\nJapan\nCzech Republic\nIsrael\nOther\nNARA\nYale LUX\nRetrieved from \"\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Nobel_Prize&oldid=1337669928\n\"\nCategories\n:\nNobel Prize\n1895 establishments in Sweden\nAlfred Nobel\nAwards established in 1895\nInternational academic awards\nInternational science and technology awards\nRoyal Swedish Academy of Sciences\nScience and technology in Sweden\nSwedish Culture Canon\nSwedish science and technology awards\nHidden categories:\nArticles containing Swedish-language text\nPages with Swedish IPA\nArticles containing Norwegian-language text\nPages with Norwegian IPA\nWikipedia articles needing clarification from October 2020\nWebarchive template wayback links\nCS1 Norwegian-language sources (no)\nCS1 German-language sources (de)\nCS1 Swedish-language sources (sv)\nCS1 maint: deprecated archival service\nWikipedia articles incorporating a citation from the ODNB\nPages using cite ODNB with id parameter\nArticles with short description\nShort description is different from Wikidata\nWikipedia pages semi-protected against vandalism\nUse dmy dates from March 2022\nArticles containing potentially dated statements from 2024\nAll articles containing potentially dated statements\nAll articles with unsourced statements\nArticles with unsourced statements from December 2024\nArticles needing more viewpoints from May 2024\nArticles containing potentially dated statements from 2016\nFree-content attribution\nFree content from UNESCO\nCommons category link from Wikidata\nArticles with hAudio microformats\nSpoken articles\nArticles containing video clips\nSearch\nSearch\nNobel Prize\n195 languages\nAdd topic","chroma:document":"[\n63\n]\nHowever, some of those early discoveries were later discredited. For example,\nJohannes Fibiger\nwas awarded the 1926 Prize in\nPhysiology or Medicine\nfor his purported discovery of a parasite that caused cancer.\n[\n64\n]\nTo avoid repeating this embarrassment, the awards increasingly recognised scientific discoveries that had withstood the test of time.\n[\n65\n]\n[\n66\n]\n[\n67\n]\nAccording to Ralf Pettersson, former chairman of the Nobel Prize Committee for Physiology or Medicine, \"the criterion 'the previous year' is interpreted by the Nobel Assembly as the year when the full impact of the discovery has become evident.\"\n[\n66\n]\nThe committee room of the Norwegian Nobel Committee\nThe interval between the award and the accomplishment it recognises varies from discipline to discipline. The Literature Prize is typically awarded to recognise a cumulative lifetime body of work rather than a single achievement.\n[\n68\