n(Hungary)\nPeace\n(\n2025\n)\nMaría Corina Machado\n(Venezuela)\nPhysics\nJohn Clarke\n(United Kingdom)\nMichel H. Devoret\n(France)\nJohn M. Martinis\n(United States)\nPhysiology or Medicine\nMary E. Brunkow\n(United States)\nFred Ramsdell\n(United States)\nShimon Sakaguchi\n(Japan)\nEconomic Sciences\nJoel Mokyr\n(Netherlands, Israel, United States)\nPhilippe Aghion\n(France)\nPeter Howitt\n(Canada)\nNobel Prize recipients\n2020\n2021\n2022\n2023\n2024\n2025\n2026\nAuthority control databases\nInternational\nGND\nNational\nUnited States\nJapan\nCzech Republic\nIsrael\nOther\nNARA\nYale LUX\nRetrieved from \"\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Nobel_Prize&oldid=1337669928\n\"\nCategories\n:\nNobel Prize\n1895 establishments in Sweden\nAlfred Nobel\nAwards established in 1895\nInternational academic awards\nInternational science and technology awards\nRoyal Swedish Academy of Sciences\nScience and technology in Sweden\nSwedish Culture Canon\nSwedish science and technology awards\nHidden categories:\nArticles containing Swedish-language text\nPages with Swedish IPA\nArticles containing Norwegian-language text\nPages with Norwegian IPA\nWikipedia articles needing clarification from October 2020\nWebarchive template wayback links\nCS1 Norwegian-language sources (no)\nCS1 German-language sources (de)\nCS1 Swedish-language sources (sv)\nCS1 maint: deprecated archival service\nWikipedia articles incorporating a citation from the ODNB\nPages using cite ODNB with id parameter\nArticles with short description\nShort description is different from Wikidata\nWikipedia pages semi-protected against vandalism\nUse dmy dates from March 2022\nArticles containing potentially dated statements from 2024\nAll articles containing potentially dated statements\nAll articles with unsourced statements\nArticles with unsourced statements from December 2024\nArticles needing more viewpoints from May 2024\nArticles containing potentially dated statements from 2016\nFree-content attribution\nFree content from UNESCO\nCommons category link from Wikidata\nArticles with hAudio microformats\nSpoken articles\nArticles containing video clips\nSearch\nSearch\nNobel Prize\n195 languages\nAdd topic","headers":"H2: ContentsH1: Nobel PrizeH2: HistoryH3: Nobel FoundationH4: Formation of Nobel FoundationH4: Foundation capital and costH3: Inaugural Nobel prizesH3: Second World WarH3: Prize in Economic SciencesH2: Award processH3: NominationsH3: SelectionH3: Posthumous nominationsH3: Recognition time lagH2: Award ceremonies and related eventsH3: Nobel BanquetH3: Nobel lectureH3: Nobel MindsH2: PrizesH3: MedalsH3: DiplomasH3: Award moneyH2: StatisticsH2: Specially distinguished laureatesH3: Multiple laureatesH3: Family laureatesH2: Reception and controversiesH3: Controversial recipientsH3: Overlooked achievementsH3: Emphasis on discoveries over inventionsH3: GenderH3: Status of the Economic Sciences PrizeH2: Refusals and constraintsH2: ImpactH3: CulturalH2: See alsoH2: NotesH2: ReferencesH3: SourcesH4: BooksH2: Further readingH2: External links","chroma:document":"Subrahmanyan Chandrasekhar\nshared the 1983 Physics Prize for his 1930s work on stellar structure and evolution.\n[\n77\n]\n[\n78\n]\nNot all scientists live long enough for their work to be recognised. Some discoveries can never be considered for a prize if their impact is realised after the discoverers have died.\n[\n79\n]\n[\n80\n]\n[\n81\n]\nAward ceremonies and related events\nRight:\nGiovanni Jona-Lasinio\npresenting\nYoichiro Nambu\n's Nobel Lecture at\nAula Magna\nin Stockholm in 2008; Left:\nBarack Obama\nafter receiving the Nobel Peace Prize in Oslo City Hall from Norwegian Nobel Committee chairman\nThorbjørn Jagland\nin 2009"}␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀